Programming Essentials for Studies in Human Language & Technology¶

Session 2: NLTK¶

Getting started¶

Introduction¶

In this session we will be using the Python library NLTK to learn the basic functions and methods that this library provides to analyze text corpora. But before we introduce them, we will need to make sure that our computer has the required software.

Installing Python¶

NLTK requires Python versions 3.5, 3.6, 3.7, or 3.8

For Windows users, download the executable file for one of the above mentioned Python versions from https://www.python.org/downloads/windows/

For Mac users you can download a valid Python version from https://www.python.org/downloads/mac-osx/

Installing PyCharm¶

For simplicity reasons, and in an attempt to make this sessions as easy to follow for Windows and Mac users, we will be using PyCharm as the Python default editor for our scripts. It can be downloaded from this link https://www.jetbrains.com/pycharm/download/. You will need to download the community (free) version.

PyCharm will allow us to create virtual environments in an easy-to-follow manner, and will make the process of writing Python code easier and cleaner. If you are used to work with another IDE, please do so, the instructions and code for the scripts will not differ.

Using PyCharm¶

After opening PyCharm, we will need to create a project for our session. A PyCharm project contains a virtual environment that will allow us to store all the software needed for the session in an specific container, isolated from the computer’s main software.

To create a project just click on "file"->"create a project" or just click the link on the interface "Create a new project", as shown im the image below.

The image below shows the field that needs to be edited to name the project. Make sure that the field "Base interpreter" is pointing to the correct Python version.

Once the project is created we can add Python files to it, where we will be writing code. The image below shows how to add a Python file to the project.

After the Python file is created, click on the terminal tab (see lower left corner of the interface), and type the following commands to install NLTK:

In [1]:
pip install NLTK
